# Implementation Plan - Gemini Code Gen, District Profiles, Semantic Cache, Guardrails & Chat History

This plan details the implementation of a hybrid AI query engine for the **AI Research Assistant**. Instead of asking Gemini to perform calculations or search raw datasets in its prompt context (which is slow, expensive, and error-prone), the engine will use:
1. **District Summary Profiles**: A pre-compiled, cached JSON context containing key demographics, deprivation ranks, and cancer rates for all 45 districts in the East of England. This is passed directly to Gemini for instant, accurate district-level lookups and comparisons.
2. **Text-to-Pandas Code Generation**: For complex queries (e.g. correlations, regression trendlines, or custom metrics), Gemini writes a Python snippet which executes locally.
3. **Semantic Code Cache**: A local embedding-based cache that stores previously generated Python code for similar questions, executing them instantly.
4. **Scope Guardrails**: Multi-tier restrictions (model-level instructions, query pre-classifier, and grounding rules) to keep responses strictly focused on public health in the East of England.
5. **Conversational Chat History**: Local session-bound conversation history. Allows users to ask follow-up questions (e.g., *"What is its cancer rate?"* after asking *"Show population of Luton"*). History is stored in `st.session_state` and automatically cleared when the user closes their session.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Code Execution Safety (Sandboxing)**:
> Running code generated by an LLM (`exec()` / `eval()`) requires precautions. Since this dashboard runs locally on your system, the risk of arbitrary code execution is low, but we propose:
> - Restricting the execution environment's `globals()` to only include pandas, numpy, and the loaded DataFrames (`df_cancer`, `df_imd`, `df_pop`).
> - Banning toxic keywords (e.g., `import`, `os`, `sys`, `subprocess`, `open`, `write`, `exec`, `eval`) from the generated code before running it.
> Please review this security approach and let us know if you have specific sandboxing requirements.

> [!NOTE]
> **Conversational History Context**:
> - We will format the last 3 turns of dialogue from `st.session_state["ra_chat_history"]` and inject them as conversation context into the prompts.
> - A "Clear Chat" button will be added to the sidebar to let users reset the conversation manually without refreshing the page.

